      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make the batter",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat the oven to 180°C fan and line two baking trays with mats or well-greased baking paper. Grease the handle of a wooden spoon. Put the {{unsalted-butter}}, {{caster-sugar}} and {{golden-syrup}} into a small saucepan over a low heat and stir until smooth; the mixture should be melted and slightly thinned but not boiling. Take off the heat, add the sifted {{plain-flour}}, the {{ginger-ground}}, the zest of one {{lemon}} and the {{brandy}} if using. Stir to a smooth thin batter.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Bake four at a time",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Drop teaspoons of batter onto one tray, four to a tray, with 10 cm between each. They spread to about 9 cm. Bake for 7 to 8 minutes; the snaps will spread and turn deep gold with a lacy surface. While they bake, set up the second tray ready to go in.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Roll while hot",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Take the tray from the oven and put the second one in. Wait one minute for the snaps to firm enough to lift. Lift each with a palette knife, drape across the greased wooden-spoon handle, and roll quickly into a tube; slide off and set on a rack to cool. Work fast, the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "rolling window is two minutes wide",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmp99a4ht0000e0v4h4ao4jhv"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": ". If a snap hardens before you can roll it, return the tray to the oven for 30 seconds to soften.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Whip the cream, fill",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Whip the {{double-cream}}, {{icing-sugar}} and {{vanilla-extract}} to soft peaks. Spoon into a piping bag and pipe into both ends of each cooled snap. Serve within an hour; the cream softens the biscuit on standing.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
